{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox film | name = Eskimo Artist: Kenojuak | image = | caption = | director = [[John Feeney (filmmaker)|John Feeney]] | producer = [[Tom Daly (producer)|Tom Daly]] | writer = [[John Feeney (filmmaker)|John Feeney]] | narrator = | starring = | music = | cinematography = François Séguillon | editing = | distributor = [[National Film Board of Canada]] | released = {{film date|1964}} | runtime = 20 minutes | country = Canada | language = English }} '''''Eskimo Artist: Kenojuak''''' is a 1964 Canadian [[short film|short]] [[documentary film]] about [[Inuit]] artist [[Kenojuak Ashevak]], directed by [[John Feeney (filmmaker)|John Feeney]]. It was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)|Best Documentary Short]].<ref name="Oscars1965">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1965 |title=The 37th Academy Awards (1965) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=August 24, 2011|work=oscars.org}}</ref>
Regarding the use of the term "Eskimo" in the title, Feeney wrote in 1993 that he had suggested using the now-accepted term "Inuit" in the film, but had been told that it would be confusing for non-Inuit audiences of the day.{{cn|date=September 2016}}
''Eskimo Artist: Kenojuak'' found new life again in 1992, when filmmakers [[Colin Low (filmmaker)|Colin Low]] and [[Tony Ianzelo]] combined archival and contemporary footage of Kenojuak in ''[[Momentum (IMAX film)|Momentum]]'', Canada’s IMAX HD film for [[Seville Expo '92|Expo '92]]. [http://www.nfb.ca/trouverunfilm/fichefilm.php?id=28411&v=h&lg=en&exp=${momentum}]
